"Voolstra C.R., Schnetzer J., Peshkin L., Randall C.J., Szmant A.M., Medina M.","Effects of temperature on gene expression in embryos of the coral Montastraea faveolata",2009,"BMC Genomics","10",, 627,"","",,,10.1186/1471-2164-10-627,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-74549224369&partnerID=40&md5=446211bdcf7d0ca11192a5859ef385f8","Red Sea Research Center, King Abdullah University of Science and Technology (KAUST), Thuwal, Saudi Arabia; School of Natural Sciences, University of California, Merced, 5200 North Lake Road Merced, CA 95343, United States; Systems Biology, Harvard Medical School, 200 Longwood Ave, W Alperts #536, Boston, MA 02115, United States; Center for Marine Science, University North Carolina Wilmington, 5600 Marvin K Moss Lane, Wilmington, NC 28409, United States","Voolstra, C.R., Red Sea Research Center, King Abdullah University of Science and Technology (KAUST), Thuwal, Saudi Arabia, School of Natural Sciences, University of California, Merced, 5200 North Lake Road Merced, CA 95343, United States; Schnetzer, J., School of Natural Sciences, University of California, Merced, 5200 North Lake Road Merced, CA 95343, United States; Peshkin, L., Systems Biology, Harvard Medical School, 200 Longwood Ave, W Alperts #536, Boston, MA 02115, United States; Randall, C.J., Center for Marine Science, University North Carolina Wilmington, 5600 Marvin K Moss Lane, Wilmington, NC 28409, United States; Szmant, A.M., Center for Marine Science, University North Carolina Wilmington, 5600 Marvin K Moss Lane, Wilmington, NC 28409, United States; Medina, M., School of Natural Sciences, University of California, Merced, 5200 North Lake Road Merced, CA 95343, United States","Background: Coral reefs are expected to be severely impacted by rising seawater temperatures associated with climate change. This study used cDNA microarrays to investigate transcriptional effects of thermal stress in embryos of the coral Montastraea faveolata. Embryos were exposed to 27.5°C, 29.0°C, and 31.5°C directly after fertilization. Differences in gene expression were measured after 12 and 48 hours.Results: Analysis of differentially expressed genes indicated that increased temperatures may lead to oxidative stress, apoptosis, and a structural reconfiguration of the cytoskeletal network. Metabolic processes were downregulated, and the action of histones and zinc finger-containing proteins may have played a role in the long-term regulation upon heat stress.Conclusions: Embryos responded differently depending on exposure time and temperature level. Embryos showed expression of stress-related genes already at a temperature of 29.0°C, but seemed to be able to counteract the initial response over time. By contrast, embryos at 31.5°C displayed continuous expression of stress genes. The genes that played a role in the response to elevated temperatures consisted of both highly conserved and coral-specific genes. These genes might serve as a basis for research into coral-specific adaptations to stress responses and global climate change. © 2009 Voolstra et al; licensee BioMed Central Ltd.",,"complementary DNA; histone; zinc finger protein; apoptosis; article; climate change; controlled study; coral; DNA microarray; down regulation; embryo; fertilization; gene expression regulation; genetic conservation; heat stress; high temperature; nonhuman; oxidative stress; temperature measurement; temperature stress; transcription regulation; acclimatization; animal; Anthozoa; gene expression profiling; gene expression regulation; genetics; heat; metabolism; physiological stress; time; Anthozoa; Montastraea faveolata; Acclimatization; Animals; Anthozoa; Gene Expression Profiling; Gene Expression Regulation, Developmental; Hot Temperature; Oligonucleotide Array Sequence Analysis; Stress, Physiological; Time Factors",,"histone, 9062-68-4",,,,"Stoddart, D.R., Ecology and morphology of recent coral reefs (1969) Biological Reviews, 44, pp. 433-498; Knowlton, N., The